Today I learned about the Stack Data Structure using a Linked List in JavaScript! ğŸ§±ğŸ“¦

Stacks follow the LIFO (Last In, First Out) principle, and implementing one using a linked list (with a head pointer) makes push() and pop() operations super efficient â€” both in O(1) time complexity! ğŸš€

ğŸ§  What I Learned:
âœ… Stack operations: push(), pop(), peek()
âœ… Efficiently implemented using LinkedList
âœ… Under the hood, push uses prepend and pop uses removeFromFront
âœ… Super handy when we need reversal or backtracking logic!

ğŸ“¦ Code Implementation:
js
Copy
Edit
const LinkedList = require('./LinkedListwithTailNode')

class LinkedListStack {
    constructor() {
        this.list = new LinkedList()
    }

    push(value) {
        this.list.prepend(value)
    }

    pop() {
        return this.list.removeFromFront()
    }

    peek() {
        return this.list.head.value 
    }

    isEmpty() {
        return this.list.isEmpty()
    }

    getSize() {
        return this.list.getSize()
    }

    print() {
        return this.list.print()
    }
}
ğŸ§ª Sample Output:
js
Copy
Edit
const stack = new LinkedListStack()
console.log(stack.isEmpty())  // true

stack.push(20)
stack.push(10)
stack.push(40)
stack.push(30)

console.log(stack.getSize())  // 4
stack.print()                 // 30 -> 40 -> 10 -> 20 -> null

console.log(stack.pop())      // 30
console.log(stack.peek())     // 40
ğŸ” Stacks are widely used in:

Undo/Redo functionality

Browser history

